==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*maðaz'', from Indo-European ''*math-, *moth-'' used for insects and vermin.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[maðo]] (Dutch [[made]] ‘maggot, worm’), Old High German [[mado]] (German [[Made]] ‘maggot’), Gothic [[𐌼𐌰𐌸𐌰]]; Old Norse had the diminutive form [[maðkr]] (dialectal English [[mawk]]; compare also [[maddock]]).  The IE root is also the source of Armenian [[մաթլ]] ‘louse’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'maða/

===Noun===
'''maþa'''
# a [[worm]] or [[maggot]]

===Descendents===
Scots [[mathe]]

